yScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Na.</span><hr size=1> Quartz is opaque at certain UV frequencies.<br>
<br>
Also, even if it WERE transparent at those wavelengths, at ~any~ wavelength, the transparency is not nearly 100%. Since Mauk2's design is attempting to transmit 80,000,000,000 watts thru a window 10 square meters in area, just the &quot;normal&quot; transparency will trap enough heat to be Good Night, Irene.<br>
<br>
This is just one of the many fatal flaws of the design.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
 <p>"Every man has a right to his opinion, but no man has a right to be wrong in his facts." Bernard Baruch </p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A> at: 10/7/02 1:45:21 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=mylenejenius>MyleneJenius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/7/02 7:49:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.csclub.uwaterloo.ca/u/yhchan/gallery/mylene/thumbnail/Mac704.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Na.</span><hr size=1> In looking for alternative materials with similar thermal characteristics to fused silica or quartz I ran into one hell of a show stopper. Fused silica and quartz when exposed to high heat... high UV x-ray and gamma flux... and neutron bombardment will do what is called solarization... in other words it is a discoloration from alteration of the molecular structure. This is a show stopper due to its alteration of transparency and structural properties. Given all of these factors governing solarization present in an NLB I can't see how it would not succumb to this show stopper. All I can think of is to perhaps use an alternative fission fuel to uranium... one ideally with a lower boiling point to relax the thermal constrains... or there may be a limit to which the NLB can be scaled. Again I'm no expert... and I can be wrong... hope I am actually a very cool concept that definitly gives one food for thought. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 991<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/7/02 9:44:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Na.</span><hr size=1> Mylene wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I ran into one hell of a show stopper. Fused silica and quartz when exposed to high heat... high UV x-ray and gamma flux... and neutron bombardment will do what is called solarization... in other words it is a discoloration from alteration of the molecular structure. This is a show stopper due to its alteration of transparency and structural properties.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Bingo!<br>
<br>
That is what I said earlier:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> ]lightbulb transparency across the ~entire~ spectrum including gamma rays, x-rays, UV, (plus some serious neutron and high velocity ion ablation), maintaining the required transparency thru-out the entire time period and avoiding compaction from the various fluxes, etc.)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->There are many other show-stoppers in Mauk's design beyond these.<br>
<br>
------------<br>
<br>
Now, would a NLB GCNR work? Yes, if designed properly, and if operated in SPACE, not from the ground. Designs by the experts have operating conditions an order of magnitude lower - but at a realistic thrust to weight ratio it would never lift its own weight. In space it would zoom like a champ (and not cause a radiological disaster in an accident).<br>
<br>
yale<br>
<br>
<br>
