g peoples brains....<br>
<br>
yales said: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> You are off by a factor of 10 in some characteristics.Your response to generic issues that affect all types of rockets was essentially a non-response. (ie. A loose access panel on the exterior of the rocket can tear loose, resulting in a cascading aerodynamic structural failure -resulting in the craft tumbling and tearing itself apart.) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Erm, I have addressed this concern by assigning a very high mass fraction to spacecraft structure.  I have read that in the SaturnV, if 1/32nd of an inch too much wire, and one extra drop of solder, had been used on all the soldered connections in the rocket, then it would have had no cargo capacity left.  While I have my doubts, it signals the razor thin physical margins a traditional chemcal rocket is designed on.  <br>
<br>
The Liberty Ship has literally TONS of mass to burn on safety systems.  I would propose design guidelines lifted wholesale from Boeing, to match the tolerances built  into the 767 and similar large jets.  Does anyone else recall the old 737 that had a 20 foot chunk of the fuselage blow off a few years ago?  The plane simply turned around and landed again.<br>
<br>
Puts things into perspective.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> BTW - your 300 MWt per square meter cooling requirement is way off. It is more like 800 MWt per square meter. Since you describe a future &quot;design goal&quot; of 100 MWt/M^2, you will have instant Melt City. (as an aside, the UV photo-lith glasses are being engineered to be transparent at the SPECIFIC freqs, not a super-perfectly-transparent-at-every-wavelength-and-high-ionizing-radiation-and-extreme-temperature-and-intense-neutron-flux mega glass.<br>
<br>
And this is just for UV photons!<br>
The TOTAL radiant flux thru the glass is 8,000 megawatts per square meter. (Thats equal to the electrical power output of EIGHT atomic power plants!) And the entire glass &quot;bulb&quot; is ten times that area. <br>
<br>
That means that an area of the glass tube equal to a standard TV screen must perfectly transmit the radiant power equal to the electrical output an entire atomic power plant. The power used by 1,000,000 homes!<br>
<br>
And that is multiplied about 80 times for the whole glass &quot;bulb&quot;<br>
(and there are 7 of these engines) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, first, where do you get 80 gigawatts per thruster?  That is a total power for the craft of 560 gigawatts, and as far as I can see, that is just WRONG.  <br>
<br>
Let me explain my reasoning. <br>
<br>
I deliberately chose the size of the Liberty Ship to be similar to a rocket which has already flown, and very successfully, too.  The SaturnV is close to the size and weight of the Liberty Ship.  <br>
<br>
I did this so that I would have a baseline to compare to.  Now, from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://http://history.msfc.nasa.gov/milestones/chpt7.pdf"> http://history.msfc.nasa.gov/milestones/chpt7.pdf </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> , we see a statement in pithy 60's language that a SaturnV at liftoff produces the same power as &quot;85 Hoover Dams.&quot;  <br>
<br>
From <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://http://www.hooverdam.usbr.gov/workings/main.htm"> http://www.hooverdam.usbr.gov/workings/main.htm </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> we discover that in the 1960's when NASA was making the statement above, that Hoover Dam had a capacity of 1.3 Gigawatts.  <br>
<br>
85 times 1.3 gigawatts is 110.5 Gigawatts.  <br>
<br>
Now, using some simple math, we can figure that 110.5 gigawatts is WAY more power than the SaturnV was able to actually harness.  Doing some <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.sunybroome.edu/~Biegen_J/asl/phy171/mod63Ex2.htm"> back-of-the-envelope math </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> , it appears the SaturnV needed about 20Gw to accelerate off the pad.  The other 90.5 Gw creates the huge clouds around the launchpad, makes big noise, etc.  <br>
<br>
Since the Liberty Ship weighs almost EXACTLY the same as the SaturnV, it follows that only 20 Gw is required to launch it, too.  <br>
<br>
I allowed 90 percent of the actual energy of the Liberty Ship launch to be lost, twice as much as the SaturnV, being very pessimistic about the ability of practical nozzles to capture energy from the very high temperature exhaust gas.  Thus, I arrived at 210 Gw for the entire ship, or 30 Gw per thruster.<br>
<br>
I feel pretty confident these numbers pass the &quot;reality check&quot; of the back comparison tot he SaturnV, and I have been pretty darn pessimistic.  If we can design nozzles to extract the same thrust from the gas stream as the SaturnV F1's did, the power required per thruster actually falls to a mere 20 Gw each.<br>
<br>
I can cross check these figures another way.  <br>
<br>
It is well known among the folks on this board that the biggest working NTR in history produced 250,000 pounds of thrust from 4.5Gw thermal output.  Simply scaling those figures by 5, we arrive at 1,250,000 pounds of thrust (very close to the 1.2 million I posited for the Liberty Ship thrusters) from a thermal power of 22.5 Gw.  <br>
<br>
So, I would be VERY interested where you got your 80 Gw figure, as it just seems WRONG.<br>
<br>
Ok, that's enough for one post.  Trust me, I have REAMS more info to post, and all of it is good for my side of the argument.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Also, if anyone here has more/better math skills than I do, feel free to check my numbers and slap me around if I am way off.  I don't think so, but as always, I will happily take any schooling given to me.<br>
<br>
<br>
