 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 151<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/17/02 4:37:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=51>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Na.</span><hr size=1> I have a question on the thrusts on your engines. Figures I've seen for a NLB on a JPL site showed a 56.8 mT engine would produce a thrust of 454 kN, or about 101340 lbf, less then the engines mass. The engines you are using are of similar mass and produce 1200000 lbf. How are you getting all this extra thrust out of the engines? <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/17/02 7:22:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=52>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.b5tech.net/art/b5/vorlonangry.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Na.</span><hr size=1> I was just wondering, how exactly does the fuel system for the engine work, and (seince no one else asked) please describe the fuel cycle for the rocket.<br>
<br>
*added*<br>
How thick are the walls of the glass bulb? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A> at: 11/17/02 9:55:00 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 84<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/17/02 10:45:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=53>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Na.</span><hr size=1> Oooh!  More interest! Me likey.<br>
<br>
Now, I will answer all questions, but I want to take these in order, so yales' further points get my attention for this post.<br>
<br>
So: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> And this transmitted radiant power must be absorbed by flowing hydrogen propellent in a space you could bridge with your arms. Even with an added absorber (which would be ejected from the engine nozzle into the atmosphere), it would be a rather stiff task. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yep, this is a thorny one.  A simple solution is to make the reaction chamber larger, thus giving more distance for the coupling to occur.  Another, more brute force, approach is to inject absorbers into the mix.  One element which I have stumbled across is plain oxygen!  I could see carrying some small fraction of the reaction mass as LOX, and exuding it through micropores in the chamber wall.  All in all, I think this is quite a solvable issue.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Considerations similar to this absolutely permeate your design. (including, *~but not limited to~*: ...-neutron management from a 80 gigawatt(t) reactor in a 1 x 3 meter container. Both in maintaining a chain reaction of such high power with such short radii (reflectors would be in the wrong place), and the effect on structural material. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Neutron transparency is an interesting topic.  The Mean Free Path of a neutron in a reactive mass is determined by the density of the nuclei in that mass multiplied by the absorption cross section of each of those nuclei.  U235 (the most likely fuel I suspect) has a nice roomy absorption cross section.  U233 might be a likely candidate as well.   <br>
<br>
Now, since the fissile mass in a Liberty Ship thruster is a dynamic gas, we have the incredible luxury of being able to control the density directly.  Depending upon the vorticity, we can make the fissile mass more dense at the center than at the edge, plus we can add more non-fissile material to the core to increase the Mean Free Path, or add more fissile material to lower the Mean Free Path.<br>
<br>
The vortex inside the lightbulb has to have an equal pressure to that which exists in the reaction chamber.  I doubt we would want to run this any higher than 3000 PSI, or 200 bar.   Uranium Hexaflouride at 200 bar is pretty dense stuff, and causing a chain reaction is not difficult, as is evidenced by the fact that scientists decades ago were able to light these up without much effort.<br>
<br>
Now, neutron leakage could be greatly reduced by running the fissile vortex greatly &quot;oversized.&quot;  IE, if the active fissioning region is the densest area in the center of the vortex and has a radius of 20 centimeters, it would be easy to have another 30 centimeters of slightly less dense, non-critical UF6 gas around it to serve as a neutron absorption region.  There would still be neutrons released from that 30 cm layer, but far less than you would expect.  (This uranium blanet serves to moderate the emission of x-rays as well, see below.)<br>
<br>
Granted, there would be a brisk neutron flux from the core, and neutron embrittlement of the lightbulb would probably demand it be replaced after every few flights, as I have stated before.  The crew could be shielded with a few meters of water, as can any other sensitive elements, and the large bulk of the Liberty Ship's structure would be made of low activation materials, such as aluminum.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  ...-radiation coupling to fluids, <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I already addressed this with the larger chamber/O2 bleed ideas above.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> ...-decay heat management, <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is actually handled pretty easily, as the spent fuel is stored outside of the thruster in the fuel vaults made of aluminum-boron alloy tubing.  Plus, the spent fuel is ejected into space usually less than an hour after launch.  Long term storage is not an issue, as the spent fuel is either shot out of the solar system or dropped into the Sun.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> ...-multi-engine common mode failures (ie software or hardware glitch scramming multiple engines simultaneously or doing a hard-over gimble lock, <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is easily handled by making all critical flight systems man-in-the-loop systems.  It is not unusual for humans to achieve reaction times of a few hundred milliseconds.  Make the first one or two iterations of a system action automatic, but any action which is mission endangering (the third scram at 3 seconds of flight, for example) require a human assent.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  ...-general thermal management, <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, the fact that your power estimates seem WAY high is the first step I'd take there.  Basically, the Liberty Ship has a huge heat sink, called its fuel tank.  Liberal use of LH2 as a coolant and using the resultant warm hydrogen to power the orbital manuevering thrusters seems reasonable to me.  Also, since all the spent fuel is ejected shortly after use, the Liberty Ship is not a terribly &quot;hot&quot; system to begin with.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  ...-actually achieving an Isp of +3000 in a lightbulb with your design, <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hey, I have seen estimates that gas core NTR's can get as high as 5000 seconds of Isp.  Getting to 3000 is just a matter of determination and good engineering.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> ...-lightbulb transparency across the ~entire~ spectrum including gamma rays, x-rays, UV, (plus some serious neutron and high velocity ion ablation), maintaining the required transparency thru-out the entire time period and avoiding compaction from the various fluxes, etc.) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Ah, now you touch on a REALLY tough one.  I have to confess, I see lightbulb issues as being the hard part of this design, so I spent a little time poking about for data. <br>
<br>
I am pleased to say, I am very encouraged by what I find.  Fortunately, there is a huge amount of research being done on absortion and transmissivity in the hard UV area due to the fact that those spectra are used for computer lithography.  I have discovered some interesting facts about modern silica/quartz material.<br>
<br>
First, please open <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.pgo-online.com/intl/katalog/kurven/7980_kurve.html"> this link </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> in a seperate browser, and go over the graph inside with me at some length.<br>
<br>
This is the transmissivity curve of fused silica.  From about 180 nanomaters to 800 nanometer or so, the transmissivity ranges from about 85 percent to about 95 percent.  Hrrrm.  Not looking too good so far.  <br>
<br>
BUT, if you will mote, there is a large red bar at the top of that graph, which is labelled &quot;Theoretical Reflection Loss.&quot;  I came to the sudden realizatin, that for the purpose of the lightbulb, we don't CARE if some percentage of the energy is reflected back into the fissioning mass.  It'll just be re-emitted as many times as required for that energy to escape!  A reflection of a photon does not impart any appreciable energy to the lightbulb!<br>
<br>
If you ignore the amount of energy that is reflected, it appears that the amount of energy that is actually ABSORBED by the silica is very small!  How small?<br>
<br>
Well, from this chart, it seems the most energeting photons, the soft x-rays up at 180 nm, the absorption is about 5 percent.  Lower down, in the hard UV to soft UV spectrums between 200 and 400 nm, the absorption looks to be 3 percent down to zero!<br>
<br>
Could this be RIGHT?<br>
<br>
Well, I then found <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.mt-berlin.com/charts/chart_05.htm#INDEX2"> this page </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> which lists the absorption properties of a material called cultured crystalline quartz.  The best grade of this material has a WORST absorption rating of .01 at 190 nm!!!!<br>
<br>
This is ONE PERCENT.<br>
<br>
All these figures are quoted at thicknesses of 1 cm, which seems a reasonable thickness.<br>
<br>
Going back to my lightbulb example, of 30 gigawatts crossing 10 square meters, if the real absorption figures are say 2 percent (due to thickness) then each square meter has to be cooled for one fiftieth of 3000 Megawatts, or a much more reasonable (but still high) 60 megawatts.  <br>
<br>
Also note, there are other materials, such as calcium flouride, which are getting a lot of work and this directly address the colorization/compaction issues.  Plus, the nanotechnologists seem to be working on the atomic structure of silica, with an aim to achieving such things as perfect stoichiometry, which researchers feel will decrease absorption markedly.<br>
<br>
If all else fails, we can just make the lightbulb larger.  Increasing the length to 4 meters would work quite well.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
As for ion erosion, I have already posited bleeding hydrogen coolant through micropores to form an ablation layer of gas, strictly to avoid this nasty problem.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> In some ways, there appears to be a series of opacities each running in the wrong direction. Maybe insufficient neutron &quot;opacity&quot; within the vortex to sustain reaction, <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Nope, the ability to control the Mean Free Path using uranium density is a potent method of sustaining criticality without leaking too many hot neutrons.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  excess opacity of the lightbulb to all frequencies and particles, <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As I just detailed above, modern silica is pretty darn transparent stuff.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  insufficient opacity of the propellent, <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Easily addressed by making the reaction chamber larger and/or injecting a small amount of an opaque material such as Oxygen at the chamber walls.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> and excess opacity of the structure to &quot;waste&quot; particle fluxes (particularly neutrons and high energy photons) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Many neutrons are absorbed by a blanket of non-critical uranium.  Making the large bulk of the structure out of low activation materials also addresses thi issue.  Similarly, high energy x-rays are very efficiently absorbed by high-Z materials like ionized uranium, so I really doubt many photons much meaner than hard UV is going to make it as far as the lightbulb.  Plus, since the core is dynamic, you can tune it to absorb or release more or less as you go.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I have not posted in detail because I am working on some computer runs of energy transfer, etc in your engine. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As always, I await your thoughts!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
 Okay, this installment should make folks eyes bleed, I wil be back with yet more later.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
